<strong><span style="color: #c11b17;"><em><span style="font-size: 22px;">Designing novel organic materials with electronic, optical, and magnetic properties</span></em></span></strong>
<div class="research-description">
<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000; font-size: 18px;">Our research aims to discover and develop novel conductive organic materials with physical properties that are useful for optoelectronic and biomedical applications. Activities in our labs involve the synthesis of new <i>π</i>-conjugated organic molecules/polymers and characterization of their electronic, optical, and magnetic properties. Our work encompasses organic synthesis, polymer chemistry, materials science, physics, and nanomedicine.</span></p>
&nbsp;
<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: 18px;">Ongoing projects include, but <i>not</i> limited to: <span style="color: #002060;"><b>(1)</b></span> <b>organic </b><i><b>n</b></i><b>-type semiconductors</b></span></p>
<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: 18px;"><span style="color: #002060;">                                                                                 <b>(2)</b></span> <b>organic </b><span style="color: #003300;"><i><b>π</b></i></span><span style="color: #003300;"><b>-</b></span><b>radical conductors</b></span></p>
<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: 18px;"><span style="color: #002060;"><b>                                                                                 (3)</b></span> <b>exotic organic superconductors</b></span></p>
&nbsp;
<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: 18px;"><span style="color: #003300;"><b><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-754" src="http://www.julianchangroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/project1.jpg" alt="project1" width="172" height="116" />Organic </b></span><span style="color: #003300;"><i><b>n</b></i></span><span style="color: #003300;"><b>-type semiconductors.</b></span> In this project, we will design and synthesize various electron-deficient <i>π</i>-conjugated structures and measure their charge mobilities in organic field-effect transistors (OFETs). We will also conduct concurrent investigations into new postpolymerization synthetic strategies for constructing these organic <i>n</i>-type semiconducting structures. Interdisciplinary collaborative opportunities in the area of organic bioelectronics are anticipated.</span></p>
&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-768" src="http://www.julianchangroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/project2.jpg" alt="project2" width="170" height="124" /><span style="font-size: 18px;"><strong>Organic <span style="color: #003300;"><i>π</i></span></strong><span style="color: #003300;"><b>-radical conductors.</b></span> Organic structures with unpaired electrons are known to display unique properties such as intrinsic electrical conductivity and nonlinear optical behavior. Despite this, practical applications remain challenging due to their highly reactive nature. The goal in this project is to design and synthesize stable radical-based organic structures with properties that will be useful for optoelectronic and bio-imaging applications.</span></p>
&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: justify;"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-777" src="http://www.julianchangroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/project3.jpg" alt="project3" width="170" height="128" /><span style="font-size: 18px;"><strong>Organic superconductors.</strong> Superconductivity is a macroscopic quantum phenomenon observed more commonly in inorganic materials than in organic ones. This exploratory project seeks to create novel organic structures in an effort to push the limit of superconducting critical temperatures (<i>T</i><sub><i>c</i></sub>). The discovery of new materials that conduct electricity without resistance at practical temperatures will have major impacts on technologies spanning electronics, energy, health care, and transportation.</span></p>
&nbsp;
<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: 20px;"><strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">Positions available</span></strong></span></p>

<div class="positions-available-desc">
<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: 18px;">Graduate students, undergraduates, and postdocs interested in joining the group are welcome to e-mail Dr. Chan directly. Students will learn about multistep organic synthesis, polymers, rational materials design using structure-property relationships, and characterization techniques such as UV-vis and fluorescence spectroscopy, gel permeation chromatography, and OFET measurements, etc. Students can also look forward to exciting interdisciplinary collaborations with scientists in the physics and biomedical fields.</span></p>

</div>
